'''Dardasht''' ({{lang-fa|دردشت}}) is a central neighbourhood of [[Isfahan]], [[Iran]]. Formerly known as Babol-Dasht, it is known for its historical [[minaret]]s,<ref name="Myers1959">{{cite book|last=Myers|first=Bernard Samuel|title=Encyclopedia of world art|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=obcRAQAAMAAJ|accessdate=27 May 2013|year=1959|publisher=McGraw-Hill|page=243}}</ref> [[cemetery]]<ref name="Smith">{{cite book|last=Smith|first=Myron Bement|title=The Manārs of Iṣfahān|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=pWvsAAAAMAAJ|accessdate=27 May 2013|page=357}}</ref> and the [[Darb-i Imam]] Shrine, dated to 1453/857 AH.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://archnet.org/library/sites/one-site.jsp?site_id=8380 |title=Imamzada Darb-i Imam |publisher=Archnet.org |accessdate=27 May 2013 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130121171418/http://archnet.org/library/sites/one-site.jsp?site_id=8380 |archivedate=21 January 2013 |df= }}</ref> The Dardasht quarter of Isfahan was one of the major [[Jewish]] quarters of the city.
== Notable people== *[[Yona Dardashti]] - Master classical Persian vocalist *[[Galeet Dardashti]] -descendant of Yona Dardashti, vocalist and anthropologist
