{{Infobox political party | name = Federation of the Jewish Communities in Romania | colorcode = Blue |president = Aurel Vainer<ref>[https://www.jewishfed.ro/index.php/despre-noi-mainmenu-127 Despre noi]</ref> | foundation = | ideology = [[Jews in Romania|Jewish]] [[minority politics]] |seats1_title = [[Chamber of Deputies (Romania)|Chamber of Deputies]] |seats1 = {{Composition bar|1|329|hex=blue}} |seats2_title = [[Senate of Romania|Senate]] |seats2 = {{Composition bar|0|136|hex=blue}} |seats3_title = [[European Parliament]] |seats3 = {{Composition bar|0|32|hex=blue}} | country = Romania | website = [https://www.jewishfed.ro/index.php www.jewishfed.ro/] }} {{Politics of Romania}}
The '''Federation of the Jewish Communities in Romania''' ({{lang-ro|Federatia Comunitatilor Evreiesti din Romania}}, FCER) is an [[Romanian ethnic minorities parties|ethnic minority political party]] in [[Romania]] representing the [[History of the Jews in Romania|Jewish community]].
==History== The FCER contested the [[Romanian general election, 1996|1996 general elections]], receiving 12,746 votes (0.1%) and winning a single seat in the [[Chamber of Deputies (Romania)|Chamber of Deputies]] under the electoral law allowing political parties representing ethnic minority groups to be exempt from the [[electoral threshold]] only applied as long as they received 10% of the vote required for a single seat in the Chamber of Deputies.<ref>[http://www2.essex.ac.uk/elect/database/indexElections.asp?country=ROMANIA&election=ro92cd 1992 Parliamentary Elections: Chamber of Deputies] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110614133818/http://www2.essex.ac.uk/elect/database/indexElections.asp?country=ROMANIA&election=ro92cd |date=June 14, 2011 }} University of Essex</ref><ref name=NS>[[Dieter Nohlen]] & Philip Stöver (2010) ''Elections in Europe: A data handbook'', p1585 {{ISBN|978-3-8329-5609-7}}</ref> The party has won a seat in every election since.
